---
import BrowserSupport from "../components/BrowserSupport.astro";
import PNotes from "../components/PNotes.astro";
---

<p-slide class="cover-internal">
  <h1>Context-aware components</h1>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      The shift: a component shouldn't care about the viewport — it should care
      about the space it's actually given.
    </p>
    <p>
      Two tools: container queries for outer context, and :has() for inner
      structure and state.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide class="cover-internal-sub-section">
  <h2>Container Queries</h2>

  <PNotes>
    <p>React to the parent, not the screen.</p>
    <p>
      This is the component version of responsive design: not page-aware,
      context-aware.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h3 class="main-gradient">The viewport is the wrong question</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>
      📺 <span>Media queries ask about the </span><span
        class="main-sub-gradient">screen</span
      >
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from right">
      🧩 <span>But content lives in a </span><span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >sidebar, a grid, a modal…</span
      >
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="zoom">
      📦 <span>Ask about the </span><span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >container</span
      ><span> instead</span>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Same content, three different widths depending on where it's dropped.
      Media queries can only see the viewport.
    </p>
    <p>
      The point is not that media queries are bad. The point is that they ask
      the wrong question for reusable components.
    </p>
    <p>This is the slide that reframes the whole problem.</p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide b-a>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1em" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">Viewport</span> pretending to be context 📺
  </h5>

  <div class="cols">
    <div p-effect="from left">
      <p class="center">
        <span class="tag"
          >Before — <span class="main-sub-gradient">viewport breakpoints</span
          ></span
        >
      </p>
      <pre
        class="small-line"
        data-label-file="article.css">
        <code style="font-size: 0.75em" is:raw class="language-scss">
        article {
          display: grid;
          gap: 1rem;
          grid-template-columns: 1fr;
        }

        @media (min-width: 768px) {
          article {
            grid-template-columns: 8rem 1fr;
          }
        }</code>
      </pre>
    </div>
  </div>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Before, the component asked the only question CSS could easily ask: how
      wide is the viewport?
    </p>
    <p>
      But the same article can live in a sidebar, a grid column, or a modal. The
      viewport does not tell us how much space the component actually has.
    </p>
    <p>
      Then move to container queries: ask the container instead of the screen.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1em" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">Query the container, not the viewport</span> 📦
  </h5>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="article.css">
<code style="font-size: 0.6em" is:raw class="language-scss">    /* 1. make the parent a query container */
    section {
        container: content / inline-size;
    }
    /* 2. the article adapts to the nearest "content" container */
    article {
        display: grid;
        gap: 1rem;
        grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }

    @container content (min-width: 30rem) {
        article {
            grid-template-columns: 8rem 1fr;
        }
    }</code></pre>
  <PNotes>
    <p>Two steps: declare the container, then query it.</p>
    <p>
      container: content / inline-size is the shorthand for container-name and
      container-type.
    </p>
    <p>
      inline-size means we query the container's inline dimension — usually its
      width in horizontal writing modes.
    </p>
    <p>
      The payoff: drop this article in a narrow sidebar or a wide main column —
      it lays itself out correctly, no viewport breakpoint involved.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<BrowserSupport
  feature="Container queries"
  chrome="106"
  firefox="110"
  safari="16"
  status="Baseline 2023"
/>

<p-slide class="cover-internal-sub-section">
  <h2>:has()</h2>

  <PNotes>
    <p>The long-awaited parent selector — conditional logic in pure CSS.</p>
    <p>
      Container queries read the outside. :has() lets the component react to
      what is inside.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h3 class="main-gradient">Conditional logic, no modifier classes</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>
      ⬆️ <span>Style a parent </span><span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >based on its children</span
      >
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from right">
      🏷️ <span>No more </span><span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >modifier classes</span
      ><span> toggling in JS</span>
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="zoom">
      🧠 <span>The DOM </span><span class="main-sub-gradient">is</span><span>
        the state</span
      >
    </li>
  </ul>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      For years CSS could easily style down the tree. :has() gives us a way to
      react to descendants, siblings and state.
    </p>
    <p>
      The killer point: state we used to sync with JS classes can now be read
      straight from the markup.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide b-a>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1em" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">:has() — the parent reacts</span> 🧠
  </h5>

  <div style="display: flex; gap: 1.5rem; align-items: stretch;">
    <div
      p-effect="from left"
      style="flex: 1; display: flex; flex-direction: column;"
    >
      <pre
        style="flex: 1;"
        class="small-line"
        data-label-file="article.html">
        <code style="font-size: 0.55em" is:raw class="language-scss">
        &lt;article>
          &lt;img src="cover.jpg" alt="" />
          &lt;h2>Article title&lt;/h2>
        &lt;/article>

        &lt;fieldset>
          &lt;input type="email" />
        &lt;/fieldset>

        &lt;ul>
          &lt;li>One&lt;/li>
          &lt;li>Two&lt;/li>
          &lt;li>Three&lt;/li>
          &lt;li>Four&lt;/li>
        &lt;/ul></code>
      </pre>
    </div>

    <p-fragment style="flex: 1; display: flex; flex-direction: column;">
      <pre
        style="flex: 1;"
        class="small-line"
        data-label-file="has.css">
      <code style="font-size: 0.6em" is:raw class="language-scss">
    /* an article that contains an image gets media layout */
    article:has(img) {
        display: grid;
        grid-template-columns: 8rem 1fr;
    }
    /* a fieldset whose input is invalid */
    fieldset:has(input:invalid) {
        border-color: var(--danger);
    }
    /* 4 or more items → tighten the gap */
    ul:has(> :nth-child(4)) {
        display: flex;
        flex-wrap: wrap;
        gap: 0.5rem;
    }</code>
      </pre>
    </p-fragment>
  </div>

  <PNotes>
    <p>Three flavors: structural, state and quantity.</p>
    <p>Structural: the article reacts to the presence of an image.</p>
    <p>
      State: the fieldset reacts to an invalid input — live form validation
      styling with zero JS.
    </p>
    <p>
      Quantity: if a fourth direct child exists, we know there are at least four
      items.
    </p>
    <p>
      If asked about performance: modern browsers optimize it well, but keep
      selectors intentional — don't use :has() as a global catch-all.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<BrowserSupport
  feature=":has()"
  chrome="105"
  firefox="121"
  safari="15.4"
  status="All evergreen browsers"
/>
